segments.text: as associate dean, as far as you recall?
Yes.
I don't remember it being assistant dean.
I believe it was associate dean.
And that was only for part time because the other part of his assignment, he, I believe, was a faculty member in petroleum engineering.
He wrote most of the grant proposals coming out of the dean's office at that time.
We did not have a research foundation, as most of us know the research foundation here at A&M today.
We had a small office that helped with some of the paperwork of grant writing.
But Dr. Winerdi was
very much into proposal writing to try to receive additional federal funds for various issues on campus and initiatives that were undergoing at that time.
And it was very successful.
Some of the staff was intimidated by him because he was high profile, fast worker, and had high expectations for the staff.
Some found it very stressful to work under him.
I enjoyed it.
I loved the challenge.
He had come from Penn State, I think.
Did Benson hire him or did Calhoun?
No, Benson actually, well, I'm not sure that I know the answer to that.
I don't know that.
I know that he had been a doctoral student of Calhoun's.
Up there.
Right.
So I don't really know which one actually hired him.
As far as you know, was he hired...
When he arrived on the campus, was he hired in the dean's office?
No, he was hired as a faculty member, I believe, and then part-time in the dean's office, yes.
Who was at the college level in those years, who was the student advisor counselor, the job that Ramsdell would have later?
McGuire was the advisor for the students.
Yes, usually what we saw was the top students, the president of the student body, I mean the student insurance council, president of Tall Beta Pi.
We saw the upper end of the students and then we saw the probation students more than anything, but we'd have the other students in between.
Let me go back to Dr. Winerdi for just a moment.
Oh, please do.
The Texas Engineering Experiment Station was being established.
And one of Dr. Winerdi's titles was, I believe, Assistant Director of the Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
And, of course, he just office...

in the dean's office as part of his associate dean but also very much from the experiment station side and that's why he was so heavily involved in writing proposals and trying to get his center for activation analysis off the ground when we were working in that area.
So that was part of his duties.
As far as you were aware in that era, what was the status, reputation, quality of the engineering program at Texas A&M compared to other schools?
Well, there were certain departments that were well respected.
Petroleum engineering was one of the top in the 50s, and of course still is today at Texas A&M.
We had a few master's programs.
I'm not sure that we had any doctoral programs in the 50s.
If we did, it was very limited.
And I know that Mr. Benson was very anxious to see more doctoral programs established within engineering.
And he worked hard at, I believe,
He was working on proposals for the doctor of engineering and some of the other engineering programs at that time.
But we had few that were established.
Industrial engineering was a well-respected department at that time.
And of course, industry hired students graduating from the College of Engineering had no problem receiving job offers and usually multiple job offers.
And that was in almost any discipline.
Now, were there any programs that, as far as you all knew, were kind of marginal then in engineering?
I wasn't aware of it.
That was not part of my job assignment, so if there were marginal, I might not have known that.
Aerospace was ranked very high at that time, still because of...
Post-war things, there was still a lot of need for aerospace engineers.
Geology and geophysics students were receiving more offers than they could handle, and certainly those that double majored with petroleum engineering.
And in every field, the job market seemed to be good, didn't it?
Yes, mechanical, electrical.
Nuclear engineering was coming into being, and they had hired John Randall to come in here and build up the nuclear engineering department.
So there wasn't nearly as large a faculty there in nuclear engineering as there were later, in later years.
And engineering buildings and facilities were northeast of the academic building?
They were off of University Avenue and Texas Avenue, yes.
All on the main side of the campus, correct.
The department heads, who were some that you remember during that era?
Well, I remember Mr. Whiting.
I guess he was head of petroleum engineering even when Don was here, because I remember Mr. Whiting.
Dr. Semang was head of mechanical engineering.
Dr. Jones might have been head of electrical engineering, but I'm not sure that he was in the 50s.
He was later.
I can't remember that.
Were there any... Mr. Burgess in industrial engineering.
Dr. Burgess in industrial engineering.
Aerospace, I can't remember.
Geology...
and geophysics were under engineering at that time, and I can't remember who was head of that.
It was not a college of geoscience at that time.
Were there any faculty member and or department heads that y'all had to handle with kid gloves?
Well, I'm sure there were, but I didn't know who they were.
Mr. Vincent kept that from us, so we
All right, back to being a student wife.
So you would leave for work 7.30 or so.
Where was parking?
It wasn't too far from the building because parking was not a problem on campus at that time.
A lot of people walked to campus from...
Were there parking stickers?
I don't remember any.
I got here in 59.
I don't remember any parking stickers.
I don't remember that as being problematic at all.
Where did a student wife shop?
Well, there was...
I first started, shopped at what was called Wine Gardens in Varine.
Wine Gardens was here then?
I think it was called Wine Gardens.
And then Early Bird Shopping Center on Texas Avenue.
I came in and there was a grocery store, I'm not sure what the name of it was, might have been Orr's.
And those two were, and there was an A&P downtown brine I shopped.
I remember having to do that.
You usually went once a week to downtown brine to buy your groceries and your meats.
And we carefully budgeted.
We tried never to spend more than $25 a week on groceries.
And out here near the campus, there was nothing you could buy much beyond what a convenience store today would have.
Is that right?
There was a little bitty place at South Gate when we got here.
We could buy bread and milk.
But I guess I never shopped there because I think the only thing that I shopped was A&P and the Overs and Wine Gardens when it came in.
And where did you go to shop for clothing for anybody?
downtown Bryan, and there was a JCPenney's.
There was fabric stores, and we made a lot of our own clothing, particularly mine.
There was a men's clothing store.
There was a Lester's, but we were careful when we shopped at Lester's, had to shop the sales because we couldn't afford the clothing.
I don't remember any other names that we particularly shopped at.
And if you all were going to go out to eat, how often did you do so?
Oh, no more than once a month.
We usually didn't go out.
We might get together with friends and do a cookout, save our money, buy some steaks, put them on the grill, make homemade ice cream, but we saved our money to buy those steaks.
I can remember them.

extremely interesting incident in which we saved our money to buy steaks and Dr. Jack Little who's just retired as president of Shell was a good friend of ours and his wife and they lived in an upstairs garage apartment down in Bryan.
We saved money to buy steaks and the guys didn't get in to cook the steaks as early as we thought they should so Carolyn and I set up the cookers and
got the fire going and got the stakes on ourselves and set it up on the driveway.
And for some odd reason, we thought we needed to move the cooker.
And when we did, the legs were not fastened as well as they should.
And the stakes went over into the gravel.
And so since we had saved her money all month to buy them, we took them upstairs, washed them and put them back on the grill.
They were a little gritty.
but we ate them anyway.
We've laughed about that story many times, but it's true.
At that special meal, what else was there other than steak?
Oh, just green salad and a baked potato, and we'd make our own dessert, maybe usually a chocolate cake.
And what kind of refreshments?
Tea.
Iced tea.
Yeah.
Iced tea.
How often did, in College View, how often did student couples drink beer?
Well, if you had any money left over at the end of the month, you might, on a Friday night or a Saturday night, ice down a few beers and drink them, but didn't have time to drink much beer.
Do you remember anybody having a problem with drunkenness, any of the student, over in the student area?
No, if there were problems, I wasn't aware of them.
And what about noise, record players or radios or TVs?
We didn't have any stereos.
We had radio and TV.
We didn't own a TV.
And our neighbor owned a TV, and they lived... We just opened our front doors.
We took the newspaper.
They didn't have a newspaper, so we made a deal.
They read our newspaper, and we'd watch the news on their TV.
And we might have had one or two neighbors that their radio got a little loud, but other than that, we didn't have any problems.
Were the windows screened?
The windows were screened.
Yes, that is correct.
They were.
But front doors were sometimes left open?
Oh, yeah.
We just left them open because it was so hot.
And did anybody ever have any trouble with theft, burglary?
No.
We probably didn't even lock our cars at night.
When you came to the campus in the daytime, did you lock your door at your apartment?
We probably did, yes.
But we didn't worry about it.
Were you all churchgoers then?
Yes, we were.
There was First Christian Church in College Station that's now an interdenominational church on Welborn Road.
Where was it then?
Where was it located then?
On Welborn Road.
And we went to church there.
Mainly it was convenient.
There was a first Christian church down in Bryan, but this one was much more convenient.
And a lot of the young people went out here and they had a student pastor that would come from TCU each week to be the pastor there.
And that's where we went while we were in school.
How big was it, members reckon?
Probably no more than 100 people ever.
75 a Sunday usually, and they had a pretty good little Sunday school class for all the different ages.
And I remember we went to the adult class and we took our child to the children's nursery.
Yeah, was Screamin' Al Nelson a part of that group, history faculty member?
Yes, he was.
And the chemistry professor that would jump out the window, I'm trying to remember his name,
Jump out the window of the church?
No, of the chemistry department.
The chemistry department windows are almost ground level, and he would jump out the window and go around and then throw in a test through the transom up over the top of the door.
I'm trying to remember his name also.
Who else were some leaders of that congregation that you remember?
B.J.
Adams and his wife attended there some.
And they still live in the community today and are at First Christian in Bryan.
And you all were regular attenders.
Did you go other than Sunday morning?
No.
I think that was the only service, as a matter of fact, because we had a student pastor most of the time.
No, we just went on Sundays.
All right, and then if y'all were going to relax, and I've got the word recreation here, what did a young couple do to relax?
You got together with friends and cooked a meal.
That was about the extent of your recreation.
And you might take in a movie once a month.
There were a few drive-in movies here at that time.
And so in the summer, we might take in a drive-in movie.
Did y'all go to gun and haul movies?
No, we didn't.
The campus theater?
Campus theater.
Do you remember any special movies that were special?
Probably the movie Giant came out in the 50s and we went to that.
That was the big movie of the 50s.
How often did you go back to Breckenridge?
Oh, we only went on holidays.
We had to have more than a day.
We would probably go Thanksgiving, Christmas.
That was probably the extent of our going back to Breckenridge.
My father died in November of 57, and so I really had very little family left there after he died.
I'm not sure we went too often.
I'd go see my sister and brother, usually at Christmastime.
Do you remember any special Christmas gifts during those student years that either you received or gave?
No, not really.
No.
For graduation, Don's parents came from New York and gave him a portable black and white TV, and that was the first TV that we ever owned in May of 1960.
So that was kind of a special gift.
We thought we had really moved up into the technology field.
And how did you all communicate with loved ones then that lived somewhere else?
Well, we did have a telephone.
Everyone in College View didn't have a phone, but we had a telephone from the time we moved in.
And so we did make a few phone calls, and then we would write cards, handwritten cards.
And that was how we communicated.
See, think how special it would be if people had kept those.
Think what a story could be told from those letters and so forth.
Let's see, and during your student years here, there weren't any fires or tornadoes or there weren't any debacles like that, were there?
Well, Carla came through.
Oh, really?
Describe that.
Really how anyway it affected us was some people from the coast came in and needed housing, and so anyone that had any extra rooms, we volunteered our bedrooms and things for that.
Did you all do that?
No, we had children.
We had Don at that time, and so we didn't do that.
Did some of the others in College View do that?
Yeah, they had space.
They did do that.
All right.
Under recreation, describe going to your first football games at Texas A&M.
Well, I can remember that how hot it was.
There were lots of afternoon games.
And it was so extremely hot.
We were not used to the humidity.
It's not nearly as humid in West Texas as it is here.
And I can remember how extremely hot and buying ice was a real treat because that was what you did to survive it.
How did y'all learn about the traditions?
Unless Don went through them in orientation, I'm not sure how we did learn about traditions.
You did stand up at the football games?
Oh, yes.
You stand up at the football games.
Oh, yes.
That was a very important part of it.
And did married couples kiss after touchdowns?
Oh, sure.
Yes, yes.
Stayed true to those traditions.
And did you all go to midnight Yale practice?
No, we never went to midnight Yale practice.
Did you go to Silver Taps?
No, we didn't.
Muster?
Yes, we went to Muster when it was held on campus, yes.
And I don't remember, I guess it was held in Guyne Hall, but we didn't go out of town to any Muster ceremonies.
But do you remember, did Muster make any impression on you at that?
No, because we didn't know any of the people who had passed away.
It made the impression it was a memorial, but we didn't know the people, so you weren't as involved.
What about Bonfire?
Yes, we went to some bonfires.
We did go to bonfires, and it was just like a stack of wood being burnt, but nothing what you'd expect bonfire to be today, not nearly as rowdy.
It was just a ceremony and yell practice.
Did the married students get involved working on bonfires as far as you knew?
If they did, I wasn't aware because my husband didn't have time to do that, so we weren't involved in that.
Now, did...
Did anybody ever, any student ever kind of spoof the marriage students because they weren't in the corps?
Did anybody ever tease you or your husband about that?
Well, since he had been in service,
As a civilian, I think they respected those that had already served some time in the service and they left us alone pretty much.
What did you as a newcomer think about the Corps?
We just accepted it.
The only thing that I can remember thinking that I really resented the most was that the

uh... there were no women in the classes uh... there were a few women in summer classes and those were usually daughters of faculty members but there were so few there and many of them told us about some of the derogatory remarks that were made towards women and so you had to be pretty strong or you were intimidated to be in that class and that they didn't think it was a place for women and we felt
We were as important as the men.
Did any student ever get hurt with you that you remember?
No.
If they did, I
tried to put that, block that out.
I remember working on the first proposal for the name change for Texas A&M for Mr. Benson.
I don't know whose idea.
It started maybe within his department or he just happened to be working on it, but I remember the first time that I saw that there was a proposal to change the name to a university from Texas A&M.
When was that?
A&M College of Texas would have been sometime
Well, it had to be before 1960, because... Oh, so, really?
Yes, so, you know, it was a proposal, it was just a, it was probably in a memo, but I remember typing it first.
And what would the name have been, as far as you know?
Texas A&M University.
Oh, really?
Yes.
I wish I could find some of that.
I've never, you just added something, I haven't heard about that.
Well, it was either in minutes that he talked about it in a meeting,
because it was something I typed and they were talking about a name change for Texas A&M.

He talked about if he wanted it to be a university, not a college, and of course part of what he wanted was to see these graduate programs developed and that was within the goals of those, they were compatible goals, to see it become a university.
All right, let me sidetrack for a second on that.
Wayne Hall,

who would later be vice president of academic affairs, said that in the early 60s, when yours truly was the author of the Aspirations Report, that of all the recommendations we made, he said the one that bugged Mr. Rutter the most, we recommend the name be changed to Texas State University.
That's what they did in Oklahoma.
That's what they had done in Mississippi.
A whole bunch of A&Ms became state.
And Mr. Rutter didn't want that.
And that Wayne Hall said that he's the one that suggested A with no periods, an ampersand, don't spell it out A and D, M in order to be kind of like a logo.
and that Mr.
Rudder liked holding on to the A and M. I can't remember the exact name, and there was no discussion about the A not standing for anything, no period, and the ampersand.
That was not part of the discussion.
I do remember that.
Because after we left here and the name was changed, I knew that there was not, I had not heard that before.
But I just remember that the word university was used on the end of it, and they were discussing a name change.
Do you remember where the proposal faltered, where it ended up?
No, and I'm not sure I was here to know the end of the story, so to speak.
At the time that you were working in the dean's office, the vice president for academic affairs, who did Benson report to?
Morgan had been president, and then he's... Well, he would report it to Harrington, I believe.
All right, and then Harrington.
He reported to Dr. Harrington.
I'm wondering if there was a vice president then.
See, I don't know that there was.
Did you have any action with Harrington?
No.
A lot of his work was sent out for us, but I really didn't have much interaction.
He might call on the phone, but to really know him and to be in any kind of setting with him, I didn't know him.
What did you working people think of him?
We were just asked to do assignments, and we didn't really question those.
So you didn't see him, really?
Well, he'd come to see Mr. Benson occasionally, and Mr. Benson usually went to his office, though, most of the time he went there.
And personality, how would you describe his personality in those years?
I don't think I had an opinion, no.
Did you all ever see Mrs. Harrington?
No, I didn't know his heritage.
We saw, we knew Mrs. Angel because we had some MSC programs, Bridge Club, and some of their wives were our teachers for, and it was free, of course.
You could come to MSC and play bridge.

While our husbands were studying, we'd come to campus and people like Mrs. Harrington and Mrs. Angel and Ms. Crawford and Mrs. Whiting would be the teachers and sponsors of the Bridge Club or some of the student organizations like Petroleum Engineering Wives Club.
That was where a lot of our friendships were made.
And did you learn to play bridge at that point?
I played bridge, but I was never a really good bridge player.
Is that where you learned?
Yes.
You hadn't played bridge before?
No, no.
What were the other student life activity opportunities other than the bridge?
Just Petroleum Engineering Wives Club.
That was pretty much our social life.
Was there a once a month social event for student lives?
We probably met as much as once a month, yes, but that's about it.
Were you and your husband aware of a guy named Wayne Stark?
Yes, I was, yes.
I knew who he was because when I worked at the placement office, I knew who Wayne Stark was, yes.
But we had little interaction with him.
And did y'all ever see Bear Bryant?
What was the impression you students had of Bear Bryant?
Well, of course, if you loved football, you loved Bear Bryant.
And I guess we expected football to be a tough sport, and it certainly was under Bear Bryant.
He was really tough on his players.
We knew that.
Were there any athletes in classes with your husband?
Yes, in business.
His protege that went to Alabama with him.
Stallings?
Stallings was in Don's business classes with him at that time.
Well, and Drake Keith.
And Drake Keith.
And I knew Bobby Drake Keith.
He's from Breckenridge, Texas.
Describe.
Bobby Drake Keith.
Yeah, yeah.
And he and his wife lived in College View after he married.
But he was a good football player in high school.
And then, of course, he came and played football here and played under him.
And I think he majored in...
He was an engineer, but I can't remember whether he was in petroleum engineering.
He was?
Okay, so I believe he was the head of Don one year in class.
Because he graduated in four years also.
Yes, he did.
And did you know Margaret, his wife?
Yes, I did, and she was a teacher, if I'm correct.
She was a music major.
Okay, I couldn't remember what.
Violin.
Okay.
They lived in College View?
Yes, after they married.
He came single, but he married Margaret, and they lived in College View, yes.
Because one summer, he and Drake Keith were working on a rig near Monahans.
And that was where her father was stationed.
He worked for an oil company.
And she was a Texas Tech music major.
And that's where Drake and Margaret met.
Because when he came back as assistant coach, he and Margaret were in the Sunday school class I taught.
Is that right?
That's right.
He's just retired as head of what used to be Arkansas Power and Light.
It's now Entergy Arkansas, but he's just retired.
And in high school, he was really a loved student, really good student, well-liked, very popular.
And when y'all were students, was there any rumor about some of the athletes getting easy courses, special grades?
Were there any stories of that sort then?
At A&M?
I wasn't aware of it because I wasn't that involved with athletics.
Were y'all aware of any student pranks?
Oh, sure.
We knew things like that took place.
Do you remember any specific ones?
None that I think I want to record.
Okay, all right.
See, now that line can go anywhere.
Okay.
None that I want to record.
Did any students ever attempt any pranks or anything relating to the dean's office?
No, Mr. Benson ran a pretty tough ship and I think they knew that.
I don't think they were about to cross Mr. Benson.
I would have been surprised if there was.
Do you know of any important proposals that Benson sent forward that became fact?
Some changes that were made during that?
Did he get some of those doctoral programs going?
Well, I don't know if they got completely implemented during that time.
I do know they were proposed.
And then the Center for Activation Analysis, the Nuclear Engineering Department was certainly strengthened.
I'm not sure it was even a department at that time.
And he brought in faculty to do those things.
And then he got a research foundation going.
And, of course, TEAS, the Texas Engineering Experiment Station, just exploded in years later.
He worked with the Highway Department through TTI, of course, and a lot of those things have his blueprint on them.
What did you all think his status on the campus was?
How did he rank?
Oh, he was the top administrator on campus.
His word was good.
Was engineering the largest then in enrollment?
I suspect it was.
I'm really not sure of that.
We didn't have a school of business at that time.
It was simply a program.
Geology and geophysics were still under engineering, so there wasn't a College of Geoscience.
Arts and Sciences were together.
The College of Education was later.
It was in A&S.
Yes, it was in Arts and Sciences.
And in the dean's meetings, Mr. Benson held his own, yes.
As far as you know, how often did the deans meet?
To my knowledge, they only met once or twice a month as a dean's group.
And I'm not sure who the chair was.
I assume it was Mr. Harrington, but I really don't know because I was not privy to those meetings and I didn't sit in them.

Were you aware ever, at the working level, were you all aware of anybody ever trying from the outside to pull a string to a board member, a legislator, or anything like that, trying to manipulate anything?
Well, no, I wouldn't.
